===Etymology===
From {{etyl|LL.}}, from {{etyl|grc}} {{term|ὑφέν||together|sc=polytonic|tr=hyphén|lang=grc}}, contracted from {{term|ὑφ' ἕν||under one|tr=hyph' hén|lang=grc|sc=polytonic}}, from {{term|ὑπό||under|tr=hypó|lang=grc|sc=polytonic}} + {{term|ἕν||one|tr=hén|lang=grc|sc=polytonic}}, neuter of {{term|εἷς||one|tr=heís|lang=grc|sc=polytonic}}.

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# The symbol " [[‐]] ", typically used to join two or more words to form a compound term, or to indicate that a word has been split at the end of a line.
# {{figuratively}} Something that links two more consequential things.

====Proper noun====
{{en-proper noun}}

# {{colloquial}} {{non-gloss definition|A person with a [[:wikipedia:hyphenated name|hyphenated surname]]}}; eg, as a [[nickname]]

===Usage notes===
:Because the original typewriter and digital computing symbol " [[-]] " (termed the [[hyphen-minus|hyphen‐minus]]) covered usages aside from hyphenation, there have been additional computing symbols created to more accurately [[encode]] hyphenation.

:Theses include: the [[‐|true‐hyphen]] ( [[‑]] ), the [[:wikipedia:Line_breaking#Word_boundaries.2C_hyphenation.2C_and_hard_spaces|non‐breaking hyphen]] ( [[‑]] ), and the [[part-time|part‐time]]‐visible [[:wikipedia:Soft_hyphen|soft hyphen]] (the symbol ''between­these­words'').

:Type, set by professional [[typesetter]]s (that is, without the use of a [[:wikipedia:typewriter|mechanical typewriter]]) has always contained separate [[glyph]]s for hyphenation, subtraction, negation, and many lengths of [[dash#Noun|dash]]es.

